1
00:00:00 --> 00:00:16
Can a simple veil change the career destiny of thousands of women? It sounds like the plot of a movie about music, but it is a real economic thriller, a fascinating mystery that takes us straight to the heart of the world's greatest orchestras.

2
00:00:16 --> 00:00:27
For decades, and I mean decades, symphony orchestras were practically a club for men only, then out of the blue, starting from the 70s, something changes and it changes radically.

3
00:00:27 --> 00:00:37
But what exactly happened? And look here. These data are proof of our mystery. Let's take one of the most famous orchestras, the New York Philharmonic.

4
00:00:37 --> 00:00:47
Before 1970, the percentage of women was... just think... below 5%. Practically zero. Today we are above 35%.

5
00:00:47 --> 00:00:54
A huge and unexpected change. But how was it possible? What was the spark of this revolution?

6
00:00:54 --> 00:01:04
Well, many might think it was a matter of time, of culture, or perhaps that in the seventies women suddenly started playing better.

7
00:01:04 --> 00:01:11
But the reality is much more subtle and teaches us something fundamental about the way prejudices work.

8
00:01:11 --> 00:01:21
You see, even the most enlightened and sincere conductors were convinced they were judging only based on talent. Yet the facts said otherwise.

9
00:01:21 --> 00:01:34
And precisely to try to break down this wall, between the seventies and eighties, something happens. An element is introduced that I assure you completely changes the rules of the game: the screen or the veil in auditions.

10
00:01:34 --> 00:01:48
What does it mean? It means that those who have to decide whether or not to hire a musician can no longer see their face while they play. They only hear their sound coming from behind a veil. And this, guys, changes everything.

11
00:01:48 --> 00:01:57
The study by Goldin and Rouse analyzed thousands of these auditions, a monumental work of data analysis. And the results were incredible. The use of the veil increased the probability of a woman being hired by 50%.

12
00:01:57 --> 00:02:08
Even the probability of passing the preliminary selections increased by 300%. A number that makes your head spin if you think about it.

13
00:02:08 --> 00:02:22
But the most interesting thing is that the conductors were convinced they were absolutely impartial. They believed they were judging only the music, technical perfection, and interpretation.

14
00:02:22 --> 00:02:44
And yet, the data tell us a different story. A story that speaks of unconscious bias, of those subtle ideas that we all have and that influence our decisions, even when we are convinced we are 100% objective. The veil didn't create talent out of nowhere; it simply allowed the talent that was already there to be heard without the filter of gender.

15
00:02:44 --> 00:02:50
But the impact of the veil didn't stop at hiring. It had a cascade effect on the entire system.

16
00:02:50 --> 00:03:02
If women know they have a real chance of being judged only for their merit, they will have much more incentive to study, to improve, and to attempt an orchestral career.

17
00:03:02 --> 00:03:16
It's what we call "incentive to investment in human capital" in economics. The fairer the system, the more talented people will be willing to give their best to get in.

18
00:03:16 --> 00:03:31
And the data confirm it: in the years following the introduction of the veil, the number of women participating in auditions took off. It wasn't just that more women were being hired; it was that many more women understood it was worth a try.

19
00:03:31 --> 00:03:41
The study tells us that the introduction of the screen explains about a third of that incredible increase of women in orchestras.

20
00:03:41 --> 00:03:51
Another third, as we hypothesized at the beginning, is due to the simple fact that more women were graduating; in short, the talent was definitely there, it just needed a fairer system to let it emerge.

21
00:03:51 --> 00:04:01
And the last third? Well, that's what we called the take-off effect.

22
00:04:01 --> 00:04:11
The existence of a fair system pushed more women to invest in their own talent. An invisible but powerful force that changed the face of classical music forever.

23
00:04:11 --> 00:04:18
This story teaches us that merit is not an abstraction, but the result of fair rules.

24
00:04:18 --> 00:04:24
If you enjoyed this journey between economics and music, subscribe and hit the notification bell.

25
00:04:24 --> 00:04:30
See you in the next video, where we will continue to discover what economists really do.